article.headline: After crushing East Carolina, Duke thinks of Vols
article.linkText: Beard leads Duke to opening rout of East Carolina
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. -- The last fans hadn't worked their way out of
the stands in Cameron Indoor Stadium before the players of
top-ranked Duke had turned their thoughts from East Carolina to
Tennessee.

	   "We haven't talked about this game for a long time, and now
it's finally here. It's time for us to put everything together,''
Duke's Iciss Tillis said.

	   "It's going to be huge,'' Sheana Mosch said. "Tennessee is
awesome. This is going to be the game of the season.''

	   Duke plays No. 2 Tennessee on Sunday in the inaugural Jimmy V
Women's Basketball Classic in Raleigh. North Carolina State plays
No. 6 UConn in the other game.

	   The Volunteers' coming seemed a bigger story than over Duke's
season-opening 108-46 blowout of East Carolina.

	   Tennessee defeated Duke last season in the ACC/SEC Shootout. Pat
Summitt's Vols hold a 2-1 edge in the burgeoning series with Duke
that started in 1998 with a 74-60 Tennessee win.

	   "I know a lot of people have doubts about us,'' Mosch said. "I
know there's people who think Tennessee should be No. 1. We already
know Tennessee is good.''

	   East Carolina coach Sharon Baldwin, a player and former
assistant coach at Georgia, counted herself among those who thought
Duke deserved its ranking.

	   "Duke is the No. 1 team in the country,'' Baldwin said.
"They've got a great team. They've got great shooters. They move
the ball well. And they play great defense.''

	   Alana Beard led six Blue Devils (1-0) in double figures with 24
points Friday night, 17 in the first half. Mistie Bass finished
with 13 points, Jessica Foley 12, Brooke Smith 11, and Iciss Tillis
and Mosch 10 apiece.

	   The Blue Devils played without Monique Currie, the team's
second-leading scorer last season. She underwent surgery on her
left knee Tuesday and is expected to miss the entire season.

	   Beard was 7-of-10 from the floor with six steals and six
assists. She made five of her first 10 shots to pace Duke to a
63-20 lead at the break. That was just two points shy of the 1993
team's record for a half.

	   She added five more points to help bump the lead to 76-24 early
in the second half. East Carolina (0-1), which also opened its
season, got no closer than 78-28 thereafter.

	   Beard also led Duke's smothering defense that held East Carolina
to 17-of-48 shooting (35.4 percent) from the floor. Tali Robich led
the Pirates with 13 points.

	   "She (Beard) has super-quick hands,'' Baldwin said. "She
stripped us two or three times of the ball up top before we could
even get into our offense.''

	   East Carolina's entire offense in the game's opening 10:37
consisted of one 3-pointer apiece from Robich, Jennifer Jackson and
Ayana McWilliams.

	   Duke never trailed after Tillis hit three straight baskets to
spark a 22-2 run with 12:16 left in the first half. Two 3-pointers
hit 1:53 apart by Vicki Krapohl helped push the margin to 37-9 with
9:37 remaining before halftime.

	   Duke hasn't lost a season-opener since a 104-74 defeat at the
hands then-No. 3 Connecticut in 1998.
